<p><b>Meritocracy</b> is a system of a government or other organization wherein <a href="/wiki/Appointment" title="Appointment">appointments</a> are made and responsibilities are given based on demonstrated talent and <a href="/wiki/Ability" title="Ability">ability</a> (<a href="/wiki/Merit" title="Merit">merit</a>), rather than by <a href="/wiki/Wealth" title="Wealth">wealth</a> (<a href="/wiki/Plutocracy" title="Plutocracy">plutocracy</a>), family connections (<a href="/wiki/Nepotism" title="Nepotism">nepotism</a>), <a href="/wiki/Social_class" title="Social class">class</a> privilege (<a href="/wiki/Oligarchy" title="Oligarchy">oligarchy</a>), friends (<a href="/wiki/Cronyism" title="Cronyism">cronyism</a>), seniority (<a href="/wiki/Gerontocracy" title="Gerontocracy">gerontocracy</a>), popularity (as in <a href="/wiki/Democracy" title="Democracy">democracy</a>) or other historical determinants of <a href="/wiki/Social_position" title="Social position">social position</a> and <a href="/wiki/Political_power" title="Political power">political power</a>. In a meritocracy, <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">society</a> rewards (by wealth, position, and social status) those who show talent and competence as demonstrated by past actions or by <a href="/wiki/Competition" title="Competition">competition</a>.</p>
